title: For Sale:  CZ SP-01
postcontent: I am putting my CZ SP-01 up for sale. I bought this gun from the original owner here on arms list about two years ago. He had this SP-01 and a Compact and he decided he liked his compact better so he sold me this one. Since then, It has been one of my competiton guns and has served me well. I have recently upgraded to a Shadow 2 so this one is really just sitting in the safe. It comes with 3 sets of sights; the stock ones, an adjustable set with fiber(i cant remember but I think these are made by dawson), and a  dawson fixed set with fiber. The front sight that is currently on the gun is cracked but I will replace it for the new buyer if they wish. The guns internals have been polished to improve the trigger as well as a cajun gun works kit installed. It has competition hammer spring installed in it at the moment with the CGW firing pin and firing pin spring and lighter trigger return spring. It has a very light double action trigger pull like you would expect out of a competiton gun. I reload my own ammunition and it runs federal primers 100% but some of the harder primers like CCI it does not like. If you would like to shoot factory ammo out of this gun you will probably need to put one of the other hammer springs included back in the gun. I can install this for you if you would like. This gun comes with all the factory parts, springs, some spare springs, original case, and owners manual. It comes with 2 factory CZ magazines and a blade tech holster with the teklok adapter on it. The gun and holster are IDPA and USPSA legal just in case you were planning on buying it to get into competition. title: For Sale:  FABARM XLR5 Waterfowler 12ga Semi-Auto Shotgun
postcontent: FABARM XLR5 Waterfowler Over the last three years FABARM XLR5 shotguns have taken the competition world by storm. A long list of technical features that have never been incorporated into semi-automatic shotguns combined with durability and reliability has made the XLR5 a favorite with target shooters. The engineers at FABARM are now applying the same philosophy to making a specialized waterfowl model. At the heart of the high performance XLR5 platform is the revolutionary Pulse Piston™ system that acts as a progressive brake thereby eliminating any valve system and allows for the function of varying types of ammo. This equates to a system that is simpler, contains less parts, is easy to clean and inevitably more reliable. Additionally, the braking of the pulse system progressively slows the action with heavy loads reducing felt recoil. Most significantly the reduction in recoil and enhanced reliability is achieved in what is the fastest cycling Semi-auto hunting gun on the planet at .31 of a second for five rounds. To maximize down range performance we have incorporated FABARM’s proven TRIBORE HP™ barrel design into the XLR5. This tapered bore allows for reduced recoil and improved pattern performance. We have even created a special competition choke tube, the EXIS DK, tuned for non-toxic ammo in the most popular pellet sizes. This choke in combination with the TRIBORE™ barrels allow the XLR5 to do what no other hunting shotgun can, use up to extra full choke without any negative effect on the firearm. As an assurance of strength and durability every FABARM XLR5 is tested by the Italian National Proof House to the highest possible rating of 1630 BAR. If pure performance is the heart of the XLR5, the extensive list of user friendly features are the brains. The oversized trigger guard, safety, magazine cut off and extended bolt handle are purposely designed to allow for full control of the firearm with even the bulkiest winter gloves. The competition bred LR (Long Rib) concept has a top rib that increases the sighting plain by 4 1/2” and allows the shooter to see down the rib with a more comfortable head-up posture. To reduce glare we have masked off the top surface of the rib to provide a camo free matte black finish and added a high visibility fiber optic front sight. Water and mud can destroy a shotgun quickly. To reduce the possibility of rust and corrosion the barrel extension and bores are chrome plated. We have also PVD coated the bolt, nickel plated the chokes and covered the external metal surfaces with camo for added protection. The synthetic stock is also coated with a Soft Touch camo process to create a rubberized feel. Scarce Vintage Numrich Arms Hopkins & Allen Percussion Underhammer Belt Pistol, .45 Cal, mfg. ca. 1960's. Made in 1876, this pistol was originally sold to the US Military as an “Cavalry” SAA. It was not accepted by the Military Inspectors, and was sent back to Colt. Colt re-worked the pistol, and then sent it to J.P Moores Co in New York for resale on the Civilian Market. The pistol comes with a Colt factory letter that shows the shipment in 1876. The pistol still has a 7 ½” barrel, and the original wooden grips, there is a faint Military Inspector’s marking on the butt of the right grip. title: For Sale:  Wartime British Enfield No5 Jungle Carbine 6-1944
postcontent: Lee-Enfield No.5 Mk.1 Jungle Carbine; 6-1944 Royal Ordnance Factory, Fazakerley, England Production/British Issue/Post-War Malaysian Police Issue; .303 BritishScarce, mid-1944 production Lee-Enfield No.5 Mk.1 Jungle Carbine...this No.5 was manufactured at the ROF Fazakerley outside of Liverpool in June of 1944 and may have been among the few to see service in Europe prior to VE Day. A possible veteran of the Second World War, the rifle may have remained in service through the Korean Conflict before being sold to Malaysia where it served with the Malaysian Police prior to being released as surplus at the end of the 20th Century. A favorite of collectors, the Jungle Carbine was designed for the Airborne and saw limited production during the war, with the only known wartime usage occuring during Operations Market-Garden and Varsity, as well as limited service in the Pacific Theatre during 1945. An excellent weapon, the Jungle Carbine was tagged as the replacement for the standard, 25"-barreled No.4 rifle, before complaints surrounding a wandering zero spelled the end of production in 1947. Despite the criticism leveled at the rifle's accuracy(as well as its legendary recoil), the No.5 Jungle Carbine was well-loved by the troops that carried it and the weapon remained in limited service with British and Commonwealth forces until the 1970's. One of the very first of this model manufactured, this early, 1944-dated No.5 would be a superb addition to the advanced or dedicated Enfield collection.Condition:Very good with the carbine having no sign of refinish or refurbishment. Stoving has dulled with flaking and oxidation spotting, and overall coverage is around 70%. There is no rust or pitting on any metal surface. Markings are well-struck, nicely preserved, and correct, with import mark present on the barrel, FMP(Malaysian Police) mark on the buttsocket strap, and matching numbers found on the receiver, bolt, furniture and barrel-the magazine being a correct replacement from a post-war No.5. Walntut stock shows heavy wear with the cartouches on the pistol grip faded, as well as a coat of lacquer applied for jungle/humid climate service. Rating as very good, there are no cracks or chips, the buttplate is pliable and in good repair, and the forend is numbered matching to the rifle. Mechanically excellent, the bore rates as near excellent-bright with strong, well-defined rifling and no rust or oxidation.
